<TITLE>Tulsa World editorial As legislator governor senator and university president Oklahoma has looked to Boren for leadership</TITLE>
<TEXT>
The University of Oklahoma regents passed a resolution last week congratulating President David Boren on his 50th year of public service Fifty years of leadership is a remarkable achievement by a remarkable man and this is as good a time as any to say so in public Login required We have used your information to see if you have a subscription with us So far we have not found one If you feel you are currently subscribed please click on the button to attempt to find your account Need an account Create one now Back Subscription required We have used your information to see if you have a subscription with us So far we have not found one If you feel you are currently subscribed please click on the button to attempt to find your account Your current subscription does not provide access to this content Please click the button below to manage your account Subscribe Thank you for reading and relying on TulsaWorld com for your news and information You have now viewed your allowance of free articles Login Subscribe You must login to view the full content on this page Throughout his adult life Oklahoma has looked to Boren for leadership as a legislator governor U S senator and university president As governor he was a reformer when Oklahoma desperately needed reform The state s open government laws requirements for recorded votes by the Legislature campaign finance disclosure and competitive bidding reforms all date from the days of the Boren Broom Brigade In 1979 he moved on to the U S Senate where he was a consistent voice of moderation and compromise Boren joked that while the Democrats sat on one side of the Senate aisle and the Republicans on the other he sometimes felt the need to pull his desk into the aisle He was consistently the most popular elected official in the state because he spoke not for party or for personal promotion but for the people of Oklahoma Oh that there were a few more David Borens in the Senate today In 1994 Boren left the Senate to become the 13th president of the University of Oklahoma and as remarkable as it may seem he has managed to overshadow his record in elective office with his work in academic office Under Boren s leadership OU has gone through a golden era of physical and academic rebuilding The university has initiated more than 35 new programs and raised more than 2 5 billion in private gifts The Norman campus has been rebuilt virtually from end to end The number of endowed faculty positions has risen from 94 to 562 The number of private scholarships for students have quadrupled And the school has consistently been among the top universities in the nation in recruiting National Merit Scholars In Tulsa Boren s leadership was critical in the establishment of the Schusterman campus and the School of Community Medicine jointly built with the University of Tulsa Did we mention that he was a Rhodes Scholar Or that he led the efforts to free Nelson Mandela Or that he established the Oklahoma Foundation for Excellence as governor and continues as its chairman today There is more but one editorial is not sufficient to sum up David Boren s lifetime of accomplishments Congratulations President Boren on an outstanding record We hope you re planning to stick around We ve still got work to be done 
